  \frac{4x - x^3}{q(x)} & = \frac{(x+2)(ax^2+bx-2)}{(x-1)k(x)} \qquad k(x) = \text{1st unknown polynomial}
\end{align*}
We don't have a horizontal asymptote from the current form; we notice that the degree of the numerator is 3, but if we add 2 in for the degree of the denominator, then we have a horizontal asymptote, but we still have the asymptote at $x=1$. Let's add 2 to the degree of denominator, instead of 1. We have:
