\end{align*}
This can still be simplified. When we have a hole at $x=-2$, it means that $a(4)-2b+2=0$, so we have a new unknown polynomial:
\begin{align*}
    a(4)-2b+2=k_1x+k_2
\end{align*}
We know that the degree of the denominator now has to be 4, but the degree of the numerator is only 3, so instead of 2, it has to be 3 in order for there to be a horizontal asymptote at $y=\frac{1}{0}$, which just means there is a horizontal asymptote at $y=0$. That means there's a hole, and since it's a linear equality, we have that $a=0$, and now we have one unknown variable $x$:
\begin{align*}
   -2b+2=k_1x+k_2
\end{align*}
We have the condition that at $x=3$, $q(x)=-30$, so:
\begin{align*}
\frac{-(3^2+3x-(4a-2x))}{(2)(3-1)} & = -30 \\
-\frac{6x-15}{4} & = -30 \\
-\frac{6x}{4} & = -45 \\
